{"/service/ndnp/au/batch_au_jacobs_ver01/data/sn84020645/00513684253/1908030201/0779.xml":{"full_text":"1910\nItlontflomery\n100,000\nlv\n1010\nmoiitgommi\n100.000\nVOLUME LXXIX.\nMontgomery/Alabama, Monday, march 2, 1908-eight pages.\nNUMBER 62\nACRES OF HOUSES\nBURN IN TAMPA, FLA.\nFierce Fire Destroys 308\nBuildings*\nLOSS IS $600,000:\nORE WOMAN IS DEAD\nfffftidywU Are Homeless sod Soldiers\non Doty,\nOsar Factories la Tfc* Hulas Aad\nThoussads Of Wnfcan Oat\nOf Ba|l*7ant-C*nf\u00ab\nOf a CU14 la Cre\nMat *4.\nTamp*. Fla.. March 1.\u2014The entire\nextreme northeaetern section of the\ncity proper was destroyed by fire\nwhich broke out at 9 o\u2019clock today\nand raped uninterruptedly for four\nhours.\nThe are* burned cohered fifty-five\nacres or eighteen and one-half city\nblocks and SO* buildings were destroyed,\nwith a total loss estimated at \u00bb\u00ab00.\n900. and one woman Is dead as a re\nsult of shock.\nThe burned section Included four\nlarge and one smaller cigar factories\nand numerous restaurants, saloons,\nboarding houses and over 200 dwellings\noccupied by cigar maker*.\nThe factories burned were M. Stach\nelburg and Company, loss 1100.000; M.\nPerez and Company, loss 150.000; Qon\nrales, Fisher and Company, loss $40,\n000; Esberg, Ournst and Company,\nbranch of Stachelberg. loss $40,000;\nFrenandez and Brother, loss $20,000.\nAll the factories carried large stocks\nof tobacco and cigars.\nThe area swept by fire embraced all\nthat portion of the elty between\nTwelfth and Michigan ayenues, and\nSixteenth and Twentieth street* The\nfire originated In the boarding house\nof Antonio Dias. 1T14 Twefth avenue,\nand fanned by a strong wind, spread\nfan-shaped, defying the of forts of the\nOre department, which was crippled by\nvery weak wafer pressure, to check ft.\nWoman Drops Dead.\nOccupants of over 200 dwelling\nhouses, thrown Into a panic rushed out,\nattempting to save but little of their\nbelongings. A Cuban woman In a del\nicate condition, dropped dead from\nshock, her body being rescued from\nthe burning house with difficulty.\nIn the big factories it was possible\nonly to save the most valuable of re\ncords. books, etc., and the valuable\nstocks of leaf tobacco and manufac\ntured cigars ready for shipment was\nleft to the mercy of the flames.\nFire Chief Savage was overcome by\nheat and smoke early In the fire but\nrecovered later.\nCttisens volunteered assistance to the\nfiremen but the spread of the flames\nwas so rapid that but little effective\nwork could, be done.\nAmong buildings other than facto\nries destroyed were the hotels and\ncates of Peres and Castro, and Maximo\nCara* six saloons, twelve restaurants\nand tern boarding houses. The car\nbarns of the Tampa Electric Company,\ncontaining twenty cars were endan\ngered and owing to the destruction of\ntrolley wires cars could not be moved.\nThe fire finally burned Itself out at\nthe extreme northeastern corner of the\ncity.\nFeeple Without Shelter.\nFully half of the people rendered\nhomeless were out of work, owing to\nthe dull season In the factories and\ntheir shelter became an Immediate\nproblem.\nI St. Joseph\u2019s Convent was opened to\nthdhi by order of the Jesuit Fathers\nand many found lodgings there while\nothers were accommodated In homes\nthroughout the city. Besides these,\nthousands of men will be out of work\non account of the burning of the fac\ntories. The Insurance is estimated at\nnot more than half of the loss.\nAt the home of Miguel Rodriguez,\na cigar maker, the corpse of a child\nin a coffin awaiting funeral services\nwas created.\nThe State militia was placed on\nguard tonight In the burned district\nto prevent depredations.\nTHAT HEW YORK FIRE.\nHundreds Of Caro Burn Ajd Um la\n92^00,000.\nNew York, March 1.\u2014Two firea that\nbrought out all the fire apparatus In\nthe upper aection of the city and raged\nin lively fashion from midnight till\ndawn today burned down the car barns\nof the New York City Railway Com\npany in Second avenue, in Harlem and\nthe paint factory of George W. Grote\nand Company, only a few blocks dis\ntant. There were 740 surface oars\nburned In the destruction of the barns\nand the loss to the company is esti\nmated at 12,600,000; the loss on the\npaint factory Is given at 1126,000.\nIt was the railway people\u2019s second\nAre within a year, the former blaze\nhaving destroyed the Madison avenue\ncar ba rns.\nThe car barns took up the block\nbounded by First and Second avenues\nand Ninety-Sixth and Ninety-Seventh\nstreets and though torrents of water\nwere poured on the blazing building the\nfire did not subside until it had leveled\nthe three floors to the ground. The\nfire started in a paint rhop on the sec\nond floor.\nDuring the progress of tlie fire the\npolice ordered scores of families living\nopposite the barns to leave the tene\nments.\nWhile the apparatus was at the car\nbam fire, two alarms were turned In\nfor a spectacular fire In the factory\nof George Grote anil Company, occu\npying a four story building on 102nd\nstreet. The paint# and oils blazed fu\nriously and within a short time the\nbuilding was In ruins.\nDr. Ell Harsh Turner Dead.\nMorgantown, W. Va.. March l.\u2014Dr.\nBit Marsh Turner, formerly President\nof W* W Virginia University, died sud\nH Nr of apoplexy. He had ap\nin ths best of health and\nlast evening consented to take the\nnomination for Mayor on the Citizens*\nParty ticket.\nCHINESE! WILL SI HR UNDER.\nMeed Japanese steamer te Be Re\nleased.\nPekin, March 1.\u2014It Is announced the\nChinese government will surrender the\nJapanese steamer Tatsu Manu which\nwas seized on February 7 by the Chi\nnese customs cruisers outside of Maoao\nwhile unloading a large consignment\nof rifles and ammunition, the rifles\nnumbering several hundred.\nIt was originally charged that an\nattempt was being made to bring war\nsupplies Into China for revolutlonlsta\nThe statement Is made by officials In\nthe Chinese government that a con\nspiracy is on foot to import seven or\neight hundred rifles and ammunition\ntherefor, and the government believes\nthat the munitions on the Tatsu Maru\nwere Intended for rebels on the Ton\nking border, but it has not been able\nto prove the act of smuggling.\nA dispatch from Toklo yesterday\nstated that the Japanese Government\nwas determined to maintain a Arm po\nsition In regard to the seizure of the\nsteamer, and that It would demand\nboth an apology and an Indemnity\nfrom China. It was stated also In this\ndispatch that the Chinese Foreign Of\nfice wished to submit the entire ques\ntion to a mixed court. To this, how\never, the Japanese Government would\nnot consent unless the vessel was first\nreleased.\nAMERICAN CAR IN IOWA.\nAutomobiles ea Endurance Run Front\nNew York.\nCedar Rapids, Iowa, March 1_The\nAmerican car In the New York to Paris\nendurance contest, arrived In Cedar\nRapids at 11:30 a. m.. today and left\nfor the west at 1 p. m.\nPasses Through Clinton.\nClinton, lows, March 1.\u2014The French\ncar No. 1 stopped here e moment this\nafternoon to take on a pilot and left\nfor the west at 4:30 p. m.\nThe Italian car passed through Clin\nton et 4:08 p. m., stopping only to take\non a pilot.\nREVISION OF TARIFF\nOHIO REPUBLICANS CONVENTION\nWILL DECLARE FOR IT.\nDelegates Are Arriving la Columbus\nFor Meeting Tn cedar\u2014Many\nCandidate* For The State\nOEcea.\nColumbus, Ohio, March 1.\u2014The Re\npublican State convention which will\nmeet here Tuesday next will,declare\n(or revision of the tariff, if present\nplena are carried out.\nThe platform Is not yet entirely\nformulated, and It is of course en\ntirely possible that Wany changes will\nbe made in It before final adoption by\nthe convention. The present under\nstanding Is, however, that the declar\nation will be a \u201cA revision of the\ntariff along protective, lines, at a spe\ncial meeting of the next Congress.\u201d\nThe advance guard (or the conven\ntion commenced to straggle Into the\ncity today but the majority of the\ndelegates are not expected until tomor\nrow. All the candidates are on the\nground, and they are sufficiently num\nerous In themselves 'to constitute a\nformidable array.\nThe convention will name candidates\nfor Governor, Lieutenant Governor,\nSecretary of State, 8tate Treasurer,\nAuditor of State. Dairy and Food Com\nmissioner. Attorney General, Commis\nsioners of Public Works (two), judges\nof the Supreme Court, two; clerk of\nthe Supreme Court and four delegates\nat large to the Republican National\nConvention.\nThe leading candidate for Governor\nIs Governor Andrew L. Harris. For\nLieutenant Governor and the minor of.\nflees there Is a long string of candi\ndates.\nGENERAL DAVIS RETURNS.\nArmy Ofleer Talks ef the Gaateneala\nRailroad.\nNew York. March 1\u2014Major General\nDavis, special minister to Guatemala,\nsent by President Roosevelt to repre\nsent the United States at the opening\nof the Guatemala Northern Railway,\nreturned today on the steamship Fi\nnance from Cristobal.\nGeneral Davis said that the Guate\nmala railroad was built by American\ncapital and American engineering tal\nent. The railroad crossed the country\nfrom east to west, he said, and was re\ngarded as a successful project.\nThe General, who was at one time\nGovernor of the Canal \u00a3one, stopped\nat the Isthmus for a week. He said\nthat work on the canal was progress\ning as satisfactorily as the engineers\ncould wish for. Steady progress was\nbeing made on the great waterway,\nthe General declared.\nSNOW IN SCOTLAND.\nPauntn Train K tails Between Glaa\nkow and Fort William.\nLondon. March 1\u2014Scotland and\nparts of England and Wales have ex\nperienced two days of the most wintry\nweather In many years. There have\nbeen heavy snow storms and blizzards,\nand railway and telegraphic communi\ncation is interrupted in many places.\nIn parts of Scotland the snow drifts\nare ten to fifteen feet deep. A pas\nsenger train was stalled between Glas\ngow and Fort William all last night\nand relief trains were unable to reach\nit for twenty-seven hours. Meanwhile\nthe passengers were without food.\nPREMIER VERY ILL.\nSir Henry Campbell Baaaerataaa Suf\nfers a Relapse.\nLondon. March 1.\u2014Sir Henry Camp\nbell-Bannerman. the prime minister,\nhas suffered a relapse as the result\nof seeing people and transacting busi\nness on Saturday.\nThe attending physicians consider\nthat the weakness of the heart is the\nmost serious factor In the premier's\nillness. He will go to the continent\nas soon as he is strong enough and\nit is unlikely that he will reappear\nthis seaHon.\nTRIAL OK BEECH HARGIS.\nCase Will Be Called In Breathitt County\nCourt Today.\nLexington. Ky.. March 1.\u2014Tile case\nagainst Beech Hargis for the murder\nof his father. Judge James Hargis, will\nbe called in Breathitt Circuit Court to\nmorrow morning. Commonwealth At\ntorney Kash expects to insist upon the\ntrial of the case.\nTrials of John Smith and John Abner,\ncharged with the assassination of\nJames Cockrell. are on Tuesday\ndocket.\nnotf/man\n;*\u00a3AD IN BED\nBody of Judge Hamilton\nIs Found\nNEW YORK LIFE'S LAWYER\nDefender of the Big Insurance\nCompanies.\nHe Wee the Corporettee At terser Whe\nv Retereed from Eerope t# Ap\npeer Before the Ieee\u00abtl*et\nlee Committee.\nAlbany, N. Y., March 1.\u2014Alexander\nHamilton, formerly couneel to the New\nYork Life and other Insurance compa\nnies and In charge for inany years of\nInsurance legislation and litigation In\nall parts of this country and Canada\nwas found dead In bed this morning\nat his home In this city.\nHe was about the city yesterday after\nnoon apparently In normal health and\nhis death was unexpected, although\nhe had been falling to some extent\never since the death of Mrs. Hamilton\nlast July.\nAn autopsy disclosed an acute dlla\ntlon of the heart.\nJudge Hamilton, who was so called\nbecause he was twice elected Judge\nof the Albany City Court, was mo it\nwidely known in a popular way by the\nconnection of his name with disclos\nures regarding political and legislative\nmatters during the insurance investiga\ntion of ISOS. He was at the time\nabroad, but returned while the Arm\nstrong committee bills were still un\nder heading before the Legislature and\nmade a sensational appearance befors\nthe committee.\nIn a speech of great vehemence he\ndenounced by name the' directors of\nthe New York Life, who. he claimed,\nbad evaded responsibility which be\nlonged to them for acts which had been\nCriticised and had left the stigma to\nfall especially upon himself and upon\nPresident John A. McCall, whose then\nrecent death he attributed largely to\nthe acts of these directors. Judge\nHamilton\u2019s speech upon that occasion\nwas a sensational climax to the sen\nsational Investigation In which Gover\nnor Hughes as counsel to the Arm\nstrong committee first came prominent\nly into public view.\nJudge Hamilton was 14 years old.\nhaving been born In Lansingburg.\nApril 29, 1864. He was formerly Dis\ntrict Attorney of Albany County. Clerk\nof the State Court of Claims and dur\ning the past, ten or fifteen years had\nbecome widely known as an authority\nupon corporation and especially upon\ninsurance law.\nThe most celebrated csum In which\nhe won and which first, brought him In\nto confidential connection with the New\nYork Life, was that in which the Court\nof Appeals sustained his contention\nthat the pension contract of that com\npany with former President W. H.\nBeers providing for a life pension of\n137.600 a year, was Invalid and against\npublic policy.\nHe was the guiding figure in Import\nant litigation for the New York Life\nand other companies In many other\nStates and even In Europe.\nCAPITOL GRAFT CASKS.\nLawyers WIU Begin Argument at Har.\nrtsburg Today.\nHarrisburg. Pa., April 1.\u2014Tho Capi\ntol contrafct trial will begin its sixth\nand probably concluding week tomor\nrow when the lawyers for the .defense\nwill submit their points of law to\nJudge Kunkle. This will take place\nin the Judge\u2019s chambers and will be\nfollowed by arguments on the points\nIn the ease Judge Kunkel desires.\nThe opening speech will be delivered\nby Deputy Attorney-General Cunning\nham on the part of the people. The\nother addresses will probably occupy\nthe court and there has been no time\nlimit placed upon the addresses.\nIt is understood that there will be\ntwo speeches in behalf of Schumacher,\nand one each for Matus and Snyder,\nwhile two will be made for Sanderson.\nJames Scarlet will sum up for the\ncommonwealth, and Attorney-General\nTodd will Conclude.\nThe law points are beiuc prepared\nthis evening and are underttood to be\nvery voluminous.-\nMan Dead\u00ab Wife Arrested.\nClinton. Iowa. March 1.\u2014Fred Dolph,\n26 years old, was shot to death last\nnight while he slept. His head was\nblown off with a shot gun placed\nagainst his cheek. Mrs. Dolph is uii\nder arrest.\nDAMAGE BY SLEET\nMANY MILES OF ICB-COVERBD\ntelegraph poles.\nThan L'anr In Time to Save Much\nValuable Property la North\nnest But Commuulca\ntloa la Impaired.\nChicago. March I.\u2014Record-breaking\ndestruction of telegraph and telephone\nproperty was averted today by a nar\nrow margin.\nSleet thaj covered wires and poles\ntwenty-five to fifty miles north, west\nand south of Chicago, and 100 to 150\nmiles east, was melted during the day\nby a few degrees rise in temperature,\nJust in the nick of time. Ice-coated\nlines, sagging heavily, had already be\ngun to snap to pieces or topple to the\nground long lines of glistening over\nweighted poles.\nThe *orst damage was east of this\ncity and west of Fort Wayne. Ind.\nTrunk systems on the I-ake Shore and\nMichigan Central Railway suffered\nparticularly. In one Instance a stretch\nof nearly a mile of poles, bearing doz\nens of important circuits to New York\nand othk Eastern cities went down in\na tangled mass of wreckage. With the\nmercury ascending a trifle, the miles\nof sleet disappeared almost as If by\nmagic.\nTonight telegraph officials had re\nstored facilities to a basis adequate\nfor Sunday night traffic and hoped to\nbe able to care for brokerage and oth\ner business tomorrow without delay.\nFRENCH ARB VICTORIOIS.\nEleven Killed In Fierce Fight With\nMoure.\nParis. March 1.\u2014Advices received\ntoday from General D'Amade, comman\nder of the French forces in Morocco,\nreport another furious fight with the\nMadakra tribesmen which lasted from\no'clock in the morning until night\n<1*\nTHE WEATHER.\nWukli|to>, March 1*\u2014Fee Alabama\u25a0\nFair Monday, txH*( shawern aid\nroldrr la north portion* 1 Tara day, falrt\nlight ta freak aoatk wlada.\n4 -i...-\nfall, the French losing 11 men killed\nand 36 wounded.\nThe French expedition had pene\ntrated far Into the country when It\nwas attacked with the greatest fierce\nness by hordes of tribesmen, both\nmounted and on foot, who kept the\nFrench troops at bay throughout the\nday. At one time the French cavalry\nwas surrounded by the enemy but the\ntroopers succeeded In cutting their\nway out by a most brilliant charge.\nThe Madakra eventually showed\nsigns of fatigue and were beaten off.\nA column of the French troops push\ned the advantage and gave vigorous\npursuit for a distance of several miles,\nInflicting severe losses on the enemy.\nDEATH OF A MARtHJIS.\nFarmer Governor General of Australia\nPasses Away.\nFau. France. March 1.\u2014John Adrian\nLouis Hope. Marquis of Linlithgow,\ndied here today.\nThe Marquis of Linlithgow was born\nin 1\u00bb\u00ab0. He was Governor of Victoria\nfrom 1889-95; paymaster general from\n1895-98. and was Governor General of\nAustralia from 1900 to 1902. In 1905\nhe held the office of Secretary for\nScotland.\nHoaera Chinese Minister.\nOakland. Cal.. March 1.\u2014Chinese Min\nister Wu Tlngfang was the guest of\nhonor at a banquet given last night by\nthe Oakland Chamber of Commerce.\nNEWS OF THIS WEEK\nCONVENTIONS IN OHIO AND IN NE\nBRASKA.\nFirst Test Case a* Law an Railroads\nand Advertising Will Begin la\nChicago\u2014Bryan and Taft.\nPolitical activity will be further\nquickened during the week by a num\nber of statu conventions.\nProbably the Ohio republican con\nvention at Columbus Tuesday and the\nNebraska State Democratic Convention\nat Omaha. Thursday, will attract the\ngreatest national Interest as politic\nians bellevo that the declarations to be\nput forth by the home states of Taft\nand Bryan will,'to some extent, fore\nshadow the party platform desired by\nthe two candidates. The Kansas re\npublican state convention Will meet at\nTopeka Wednesday and the Louisiana\nrepublican Btate convention the same\nday.\nSecretary Taft will deliver a num\nber of addresses during the week,\nspeaking Monday at Springfield and\nRltohburg. Mass., and Tuesday even\ning at Boston.\nGovernor Hughes will be the guest\nat a dollar dinner at Poughkeepsie\nSaturday. _\nMr. Bryan wHl attend the Omama\nconvention and wUl therefore make-ho\noutside speeches tMs week.\nImportant developments dre antic\nipated In the disputes arising from\nthw reductions as sdfcctlve In jKaceh\nby a number of rallweya These affect\npractically all branches of organised\nrailway, labor and negotiations are\nIn progress between the companies con\ncerned and their employee.\nThe first test case against that ac\ntion of the rate law which prohibits\nrailways from giving transportation in\nexchange for advertising Is scheduled\nto begin In Chicago Monday. The\ncase Is that of the government against\nthe Chicago, Indianapolis and Louis\nville Railroad. Tha ease Is felt to In\nvolve the whole principle of the law\nIn question and will be watched with\nkeen Interest.\nThe long deferred meeting of the\nstockholders of the Illinois Central\nRailroad for the control of which E.\nH. Harrlman and 8tuyvesant Fish have\nwaged a Contest both In and out of the\ncourts. Is scheduled to be held In\nChicago Monday;\nMonday will begin the trial of Ray\nmond Hitchcock, the actor under in\ndictment on chargee brought by young\ngirls.\nThe South Carolina legislature will\nconvene Tuesday to \u00abeot a successor\nto the late Senator Latimer.\nIn the out-oNdoor world, chief In\nterest will center In the Ormond-Day\ntona automobile races which begin\nMonday.\nTuesday at Los Angeles. Britt and\nNelson will meet In a ten round bout.\nWROTE COURT'S OPINION\nWHILE IN A TRANCE\nChattanooga, Tenn.. March 1\u2014A re\nmarkable etory haa Just come to light\nhere o< an opinion of the Supreme\nCourt of Tennessee affirming the death\nsentence of Andrew Williams, a negro,\nIn mo.\nThe opinion was written by the Chief\nJustice of the Supreme Court when he\nwas in a sub-conscious condition, a\ntrance or In the midst of a somnabulis\ntic state and file remarkable thing\nwas that his opinion was thoroughly\nsound both as to the law and the facts,\nand is one of the reported opinions, be\ning printed and an authority to this\nday on the technical law points in\nvolved\nJustice Nicholson was the man who\nwrote the opltiion and Peter Turney,\nafterwards Governor of Tennessee, saw\nhim arise frpm his bed. write the\nlengthv document and retire again\nNext day Justice Nicholson had no rec\nollection of the incident. The elab\norate opinion covered all the facts cit\ned numerous court decisions and ended\nwith an affirmation of the court be\nlow. _\nT<etters from the late Governor Tnr\nnev. In the possession of one of Chat\ntanooga\u2019s most prominent attorneys\ncorroborate the foregoing story.\n\nS CONGREGATION OVERCOME 4\na BV GAS at THE SERWCE 4\nDetroit. Mich.. March 1.\u2014A de-\na fectlve furnace In the basement\nof the Gregg Avenue Baptist\n\n\n\nChurch here today tilled the small\n4 edince with gas before the con\ngregation realised It was escaping,\nk an<i a dozen people were overcome\n4 so that they required the services\nof a physician.\nk a young boy was taken sick\nk flrgt and the pastor Interrupted\ny services while the lad was car\n4 rled to the rear of the church and\nt given attention for the apparently\n4 mysterious illness whl9h had\n4 come upon him. The boy was soon\n4 followed by others, and it was\n4 finally discovered that gas was\n4 literally pouring Into the church\n4 through all of the registers.\n4 There were about forty persons\n4 present at the morning service,\n4 and six or seven of them required\n4 medical attention for several\n4 hours during the afternoon.\n\n\n\n\n\nCOMPLY WITH\nNINE-HOUR LAW\nRailroads Arranging to\nEnforce It.\nBEARS BOWK ON PUBLIC\nLarge Number of Stations Will Be\nClosed.\nOfficial* Who Were Heard la Wash\nington Unite ia Oplelon That\nReturn of Prosperity Will\nBe Sadden.\nWashington, March 1\u2014American\nRailways nave made arrangements to\ncomply with the provisions of the nine\nhour law.\nThe operation of the law will mean\nthe employment by railroad companies\nof several thousand additional opera\ntors and the closing of a large number\nof small stations on the fourth of\nMarch.\nThe discontinuance of railway service\nat many points. It Is realised, will in\nduce at least temporary Inconvenience\nto the traveling and shipping public,\nbut. In order to reduce operating ex\npenses which now seems necessary, the\noperating officials of the railways be\nlieve that this Is the ony way they pos\nstbly can meet the situation with\nwhich they are confronted.\nDuring the hearing of applications\nfor an extension of the nine hour law\nby the Interstate Commerce Commis\nsion. some astounding statements were\nmade by the operating officials of im\nportant railways. A good many lines,\nowing to a raduction In their revenues\nand to their Inability to command the\ncash necessary to meet their pay rolls,\nhave been forced, during the past four\nmonths, almost to the point of asking\nfor receivers.\nIn the opinion of railway official*,\nexpressed at the hearing.' under oath,\nand In private conversation, this condi\ntion does not seem to have been due to\ntbs enforcement of regulative law* or\nto the Incapacity of railway manage\nment. Most of the railroad officials\nattribute the rfifllculty to the unfortu\nnate banking situation which devel\noped last September. The railway# did\nnot feel the stringency In money until\nabout the ffrst of November. In fact,\nthe month of October wa# on* of the\nbest In the history of the business of\nAmerican railroading.\nOne railway official ventures the\nstatement that In the country today\nthere are 30\u00ab,000 Idle freight care and\none dine which he instanced wa* declar\ned tb be hauling empty care backward\nand forward because It had not yard\nroom or sidings to accommodate them.\nNot a single official of a slngl# ralD\nway line who appeared beforrfthe Com\nmission has expressed the belief that\nthe present Industrial depression would\nbe lasting. In the testimony of near\nly every witness before the Commission\nthere wa* a note of confidence because\nall of. them practically believed that the\nstringency In the money market from\nwhich the country haa suffered Is not\ndue to fundamental cause*. They point\nout that the crops last year were good;\nthat prices were excellent: that Indus\ntrial enterprises throughout the coun\ntry were flourishing. It wa* merely\nthe Inability to command ready caah\nand the hoarding of money by panic\natrlcken Individuals which produced so\nsuddenly the romarkable depression\nfrom which all have suffered.\nThey practically uniformly express\nconfidence that the return of prosperity\nwill be almost as sudden as the com\nTnm of adversity, an* In their argu\nments as to the enforcement of the\nnine-hour law they pointed \"\"\u2018/pro*!\nCommission that such a p\ntrSoSai'\n,.nJ.r It alScJU\nthe services of competent operators in\nsufficient numbers to meet the nee\nof prosperous conditions._\nICiTbOATS IN COlUSWN.\nKilled ss\n_ the Lawrence\nrtown NBY* March 1.\u2014In a\n^between Ice boat. running\nlies an hour upon the *>t.\nRWer opposite Clayton Hoy\naged 11 y\u00abars. son of Fred\na steamboat engineer at the\nnd Islands, was killed today and\nnpanlon. Ho. well Sherman. 13\nf age. was badly Injured.\nrBe lee boat. In command of\n5 Coppemoll and Howard Kemp,\nung men, struck the email craft\nthe two boys were sailing\noccupants of both boats were\noff and O'Brien's head struck\nst. splintering his skull.\nWARNS TOBACCO MEN\nuNiauE statement issued by w.\nB HAWKINS.\nOriginator of Mevesseal la Kentucky\nTells the Producers to Eapect\nSerious Trouble If They\nPlaut Crop.\nLexington. Ky.. March 1.--W. B.\nHawkins, the man who originated the\ntobacco growers movement five years\nigo .nd w.s the flrst President of the\nBurley Tobacco Association, tomorrow\nwill publish in a card a warning.\nThe substance of the warning in\npart follows:\n\u201cWhen your plant bed is scraped or\nyour barn burned send to Governor\nWillson and he will let you have a\nbattalion of soldiers and a Gatling\ngun to protect your property, and\nmaybe save you from a whipping.\n\u201cThere is an old saying, 'X do not\ncare to buy a lawsuit.' Do you care to\nbuy trouble In this way by flying in\nthe face of public opinion and also in\nthe face of determined men who be\nlieve you their worst enemy and who\nwill stop at nothing to right their sup\nposed wrongs. The majority has said\n\u2022No crop In 1808.' What will you do.\nsow your beds and begin a year of tor\nment. for it will be 365 days of h\u20141\nfor you, sleepless nights, alarm at ev\nery noise. What are riders doing now?\nAre they only scraping plant beds, or\nare they after my barn, or, oh. horrors,\nare they after my back with their\ndamnable switches?\n\u201cDo not hug to yourself a delusion\nand say, 'It won't come to me.' Hasn't\nIt come to the highest?\n\u2018Flee from the wrath to come,\u2019 for\nif ybu plant tobacco, you are sowing a\nwhirlwind. Muttertngs and mumblings\nare heard on all sides and the out\nraged farmers will not stand persecu\ntion always, and I say to you, that in\nmy opinion trouble will corns to you if\nyou plant a crop In 1808.\"\nAVALANCHE\nDEALS DEATH\nThirteen Persons Crash\ned to Death*\nAIR PRESSURE WRECKS HOTEL\nOccupants Are Warned by Children\nTeo Late.\nA* Americas Engineer Among the Bead\nat- Noppeaatela, Where Ha\nWat Installing Machinery\nFar Taaaeltag.\nBerne. Switzerland. March 1.\u2014An\navalanche descended today near the\nvillage of Noppenateln. The enormous\natmospheric pressure which accom\npanied It. demolished a hotel at the\nmouth of the Lochberg tunnel works,\nkilling thirteen persons and Injuring\nfifteen others.\nThe occupants of the hotel, number\ning thirty, were surprised while seated\nat the table, by sinister rumblings.\nAlmost Immediately two children rush\ned Into the dining room %nd screamed,\n\"Au avalanche! an avalanche!\u201d There\nwas a rash to escape, but the building,\nwhich wAs of a temporary nature, col\nlapsed without warning. Both of the\nchildren were killed along with many\nof those they had'sought to save.\nAmong the others ktUed was an\nAmerican engineer named Mervart, who\nwas Installing AmertcAn machinery to\nbe used for tunneling.\nThe hotel had been erected by the\ntunnel contractors for the convenience\nof the engineers, and others engaged\nIn construction work. There were no\ntourists there.\nThe village postofHce and police sta\ntion also were seriously damaged by\nthe air wave, an.d were keeled over to\nan angle of fdrty-flve degress, making\noccupancy Impossible. The tunnel\nworks were not damaged.\nFLOTILLA AT CALLAO\nOFFICER* REPORT A It'CCBSim\nVOYAGE!.\nRounding I p Sailors Whs Were Left\nBeblsd la Pernvlan Port\u2014Coor\nteslea Shows By Chilean.\nORcmA\nCallao. March 1.\u2014The American\ntorpedo boat flotilla, whloh left Talcn\nhuano on Feb. 2*. arrived here today.\nThe commander of tha flotilla, lieu\ntenant H. I. Cone, declared that\nthroughout the voyage. 1,800 knot< the\nweather was fine and conditions each\nthat good time to the Perwiaa pert\nwas possible. The destroyers arrived\nIn splendid condition, not a bitch hav\ning occurred.\nLieutenant Cohe speaks highly of the\nhospitality received at the hands of\nthe Chileans, and wad partielarly\npleased with the services rendered by\nLieutenant-Commander Ramos of the\nChilean navy, who acted In the ca\npacity of pilot through the Inner pas\nsage from Punt a Arenas to Talcs\nhouano.\nIt Is expected that the fleet will re\nmain her# until March 5. sailing on\nthat date for Panama. The Panther\ndid not leave with the battleships\nwhich sailed yeeterday. being ordered\nto remain at \u2018the port for a number of\nsailors who were missing St the time\nof the fleet's departure. It Is said that\nthese will be rounded up. as measures\nhave been taken to keep a careful\nwatoh for th# men who failed to report\nfor duty.. As a matter of fact, those\nnumber few. and in all the nuniber of\ndeserters at the various ports at whloh\nthe fleet touched is a minimum.\nPrior to the departure of the battle\nships, 721 mall bags which had Just\narrived, were put aboard the ships.\nPresident Pardo presented to each of\nthe admirals a bandsomely-bound book\non Peru.\nSURPRISE FOR EVANS.\nHe May Be a Vlee Admiral Whea He\nReaches Frisco.\nWashington. March 1.\u2014In a quiet\nway naval offlcera in Washington are\nendeavoring to arrange a moot agree\nable surprise for Admiral Evans when\nthe battleship fleet .under his com\nmand. sails through the Golden Gate\nand completes tha Pacific crulae.\nIt Is proposed to greet the Rear Ad\nmiral with a commission as Vice Ad\nmiral of the American navy. Of\ncourse, the success of this undertak\ning depends upon Congress, but the\nPresident has done his part In mak\ning a proper recommendation to that\nbody for the re-establtshment of that\nnaval grade and It Is not doubted that\nCongress can be Induced to act upon\nthe recommendation In season to en\nsure the issue of Admiral Evans\u2019s com\nmission before the completion of the\npresent cruise so that he may bear\nthe title of Vice Admiral for the few\nmonths that will Intervene between his\narrival at San Franeisco and his re\ntirement from active service.\nSuspicions Warships./\nHonolulu. March 1\u2014Some unknown\nwarships have been reported seen on the\nhorizon off thss north end of Oahu. Just\nbefors sundown last night.\nJOHN CAMPBELL KILLED.\nIs la\n\u2022ha Rennie, Hlo Stepbrother\nJail.\nCumberland, Md.. March L\u2014John\nampbell. 22 years old, was shot and\ntiled at the home of hi* *tep-brother,\n>hn Rennie, at Midland, this county,\nirly this morning. Renn.e Is In Jail\nlarged with the crime.\nJust before the shooting Rennie tried\nkill his wife because she refused to\n>ok a chicken at 3 o'clock In the morn\nig She was burned by the flash of\npistol, but fled and returned later\nith neighbors, when Campbell was\n,und to have been shot. The man are\nild to have been drinking.\n\u201cPROSPERITY COSVBTTIOS.\"\nSpeakers of N*U*ul Rffldllo* to be\nla Baltimore.\nBaltimore.' March t\u2014Under the aus\npices of the Travelers and Merchants\nAssociation a -Prosperity Convention\nwill open tomorrow and continue four\ndays. Speakers of national reputation\nwill make addresses.\nGovernor Austin U Crothers and\nMayor J. Barry Mahool will welcome\nthe delegates on behalf of the State\nand city Tuesday night.\nThe purpose of the convention is to\nrestore confidence by showing favor\nable business conditions in the sections\nfrom which the delegates come\nFULTON BILL\nUNREASONABLE\nInterstate Commission\nAnalyzes It\nWOULD WORK A HARDSHIP\nOne Shipper Could Dictate to Rail\nroad Companies,\nOpposes Menorca Which Beak Advaaeo\nla Rates Whea Shippers Pretest.\nMight laris\nWashington, March I_Responding\nitafs riT \u00b0f ln2ulry ,rom th\u00ab Inter*\nTmerc* Committee of the Sen\nate the Interstate Commerce Commts\nslon has written a letter taking po\n?ne\u00b0r.l,L8!.n*'t0r Fulton\u2019\u00bb bill prohibit I\ncompanies from advancing\nratea In the face of a proteat made by\nshippers until the commission shall\nhave passed on the reasonablneas of\nthe Increase.\n\"To give to the protest of a aingle\nShipper the effect 'of preventing the\not \u00abny rate until the rea\nsonablness of that advance waa af\nfirmatively determined by the commis\nsion,\" says the letter, \"would establish\na hard and faat rule of doubtful fair\nness to the railroads and questionable\nadvantage to the public. Under exist\nlog conditions we are of the opinion\nthat It would be unwise to adopt the\narbitrary limitation which thla bill pro\nposes. whatever may be found desira\nble or necessary In thla regard In the\nfuture.\u201d\nThe commission also finds\ntlon to the bill in pqnaUMl\ncreased burdens ufSon the\nOn this point theT commissioners say:\n\"If every proposed advance had to\nbe Investigated by the commission and\nofficially sanctioned befor-j It coutc\ntake effect, the number of cases to b\u00ab\nconsidered would presumably be at\ngreat as to render their prompt dis\nposition almost Impossible. In fo\nstances of Justifiable Increase the ne\ncessary delay resulting from the prob\nable volume of cases would work In\njustice to the carriers. Until condi\ntions become more stable and the sub\nstantive provisions of the act are more\ncompletely observed In railway tarlffi\nand practice we entertain the belief\nthat wider attitude llacretlon on\nthe part of the earners than this\nmeasure allows should be permitted.\"\nThe commission also suggests as s\npossible effect of the bill the preven\ntion of voluntary reductions of rates.\n\"If,\u201d it says, \u201cno rate could b* In\ncreased without the approval of the\ncommission after affirmative showing\nby the carrier tt might happen that\nmany reductions now voluntarily ac\ncorded would not be made.\u201d\nBODY OK KATHKIt LKU.\nTea Thousand Persons Look on thr\nRemains.\nPaterson, N. J., March 1.\u2014Ten thou\nsand persons today looked upon the\nface of Rev. Father Leo Heinrichs, 8.\nO. F. M.. at St. Bonaventure Monas\ntery, in which the murdered priest was\nfor years the pastor.\nThe body lay in state from noon un\ntil 11 o'clock tonight and during the\nnine hours an unbroken procssalon of\nmourners passed the bier. So great\nwas the throng that a detail of fifty\npolice was secured to maintain the\nformations of two lines that extended\nfor blocks.\nThrough a succession of snow, sleet\nand rain storms outside, the parish\nioners stood for hours patiently wait\ning thair turns. There was no unto\nward demonstration.\nBecause of failing hsaltb Father Leo\nwas transferred last September to Den\nver where at tha chancel rail of St.\nElizabeth Church last Sunday he was\nshot and killed by the avowed anarch\nist known as Oulseppi Alio.\nThe funeral will be held tomorrow\nmorning when solemn requiem mass\nwill be sung by Rev. Father Edward\nBlecke, assisted by the forty or moro\nmonks and lay brothers in St. Bona\nventure's monastery.\nBishop John J. O'Connor of the Ro\nman Catholic diocese of Newark and a\nnumber of other high dignitaries will\nbe present.\nTRAIN KILLS TWO.\nFrederick George sad Hsrfy Tocher\nare Croaked. 1\nBaltimore, ^(arch 1.\u2014Frederick\nGeorge and Harry Tucker were killed\ntoday by an express train of the Bal\ntimore and Ohio Railroad, tha former\nlosing his life lit an endeavor to save\nthe latter.\nThe two men. with a companion, had\ntaken to the railnoad track as a short\ncut to their homes, and had stepped\nfrom one track to another to get out\nof the way of a freight train that was\napproaching from in front of them.\nSoon afterwards, looking back for'\nTucker, who had fallen to the rear,\nGeorge saw an express train approach\ning rapidly. He ran back yelling a\nwarning to Tucker, but seems not to\nhave been understood and both were\nstruck and instantly killed.\nTO PRESERVE THE GAME.\nCleveland and Roosevelt Write Letter*\nte Sportsmen.\nMontclair. N. J.. March 1,\u2014President\nRoosevelt has expressed a desire that\nthe movement In New Jersey for the\npreservation of game shall succeed and\nin a letter to George Patton of Mont- a\nclalr. President of the Association of\nNew Jersey Sportsmen, declares against\nthe indiscriminate slaughter of wild\nfowls.\nGrover Cleveland has also written a\nletter declaring himself in sympathy,\nwith the movement to end spring an<[\nsummer shooting.\nPOLE BURN TO DBATTH.\nSob Risks Hla Life Trying to Save\nFamily.\nBuffalo. N. Y.. March J.\u2014Anthony\nSchultx. 511 years old and three of hit\nchildren. Nollie 13. Joseph 11 and May\nR years old. were burned to death in\na lire in their home in Depew. ten\nmiles from here today. Mre. Schulte\nand her four youngest children were\nrescued.\nWalter Schultx a married son who\nlived next door, risked his life twice\nIn rescuing his mother and the young,\ner children.\nRoyal Baby Expected.\nMadrid. March 3.\u2014It to officially an\nnouncement that the acouchement of\nQueen Victoria Is expseted to take\nplace about the end of July,","height":"27692","width":"20240"}}
